            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">Ibn ʿArabi’s collected poems, containing more than 800 verses, compiled in the last years of his life and finished in 634H. There are are several different versions of the work, including a six volume holograph of which we do not, at the moment, have a complete copy. Research is therefore ongoing to produce a definitive version of the whole text. The best-known version is the printed edition produced by Bulaq, which only reproduces one volume. An analysis of the different versions can be found in Cook/Hirtenstein: The Great Diwān and its offspring; the collection and dispersion of Ibn ʿArabī’s poetry, in JMIAS 52, 2012.</note>
               <note type="biblioComments">OY lists 28 mss, of which at least four are historic. The best is Khalili 225, which is volume (juzʾ) 4 of the holograph, dated 634H in Damascus. The other holographs, Yusuf Aga 5502 and 5503, were stolen without being previously microfilmed, so there is no access to the texts, although it is believed that Uni 1438 is a copy of the first part.</note>
